post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_20062515_20062581_0": {"length": 25, "quality": 0.9259259259259259, "section_id": 482}}, "n3337": {"so_20062515_20062581_0": {"length": 25, "quality": 0.9259259259259259, "section_id": 473}}}, "20062515": {"ViewCount": "155", "Body": "<p>I just learned today that it's possible to inherit a constructor with a <code>using</code> statement: <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/20062289/5987\">https://stackoverflow.com/a/20062289/5987</a></p>\n<p>The question is if this is specified by the standard or if it's an extension by certain compilers. If it is part of the standard, was it introduced in C++11?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "20062581", "Title": "Is inheriting constructors part of the standard?", "CreationDate": "2013-11-19T03:21:55.673", "Id": "20062515", "CommentCount": "0", "FavoriteCount": "2", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T12:19:12.750", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "LastActivityDate": "2013-11-19T03:27:52.427", "Score": "3", "OwnerUserId": "5987", "Tags": "<c++><inheritance><c++11><constructor>", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "20062583": {"PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It was introduced in the C++11, but as mentionned in the previous question, since it is fairly new, only a few compilers support this feature.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-11-19T03:27:52.427", "Id": "20062583", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2013-11-19T03:27:52.427", "ParentId": "20062515", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "2908963"}, "20062581": {"PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Yes, it's standard. Yes, it was added in C++11:</p>\n<p>C++11 \u00a7 12.9 Inheriting Constructors [class.inhctor]:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_20062515_20062581_0\">A <em>using-declaration</em> (7.3.3) that names a constructor implicitly declares a set of <em>inheriting constructors</em>. The\n  <em>candidate set of inherited constructors</em> from the class <code>X</code> named in the <em>using-declaration</em> consists of actual\n  constructors and notional constructors that result from the transformation of defaulted parameters as follows:\n  ...</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-11-19T03:27:37.260", "Id": "20062581", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2013-11-19T03:27:37.260", "ParentId": "20062515", "Score": "5", "OwnerUserId": "923854"}});